<br>
I just wanted to send an open letter to whoever it was that decided in the past few weeks that it'd be cute to undercut the market on solstice robe prices.<br>
<br>
The robe is only useful for the xanthe/solstice quest. Customers either need a robe, or they don't. Nobody is sitting out there waiting for our prices to hit a magic number and then they'll buy... it's not like &quot;BD 2500&quot;, pass, &quot;BD 2000&quot;, pass, &quot;BD 1500&quot;, now I'll buy that instead of farming em myself. The market is limited to the people who are doing the quests, and the supply is likewise limited to no more than a dozen tailors willing to put in the time to make these for resale.<br>
<br>
Sure, by being 50pp cheaper than others, if someone plans to buy a robe anyway and they check /bazaar, you'll probably pick up more sales than the people you're undercutting. But those people -- myself and several other high level tailors that I talk to occasionally and have (as far as I know) an amicable relationship with -- will generally give a mental shrug and match your price. We like all being at the same price, because then our share of the buying public is fair... it's either random luck, or where you choose to set up shop, or perhaps buyers who've dealt with you before or prefer dealing with one guild over another, etc. Customers need robes, and all of us holding the same price will eventually sell robes.<br>
<br>
Start undercutting prices, and everyone else drops to match. Now, personally, I think that 3k was a fair price for the time, up front costs, and skill involved. But hey, if you don't that's fine. Is 2750 fair? 2500? Cause I'm here to tell you, I can sell these suckers at 1k and still make a profit. Do you really want your little undercut -&gt; price match -&gt; undercut war to end you up at 1k for robes?<br>
<br>
Customers who read that might be thinking &quot;holy *&amp;%^ she makes money at 1k and I've been payin 3?&quot; Well, yes. But my skill is 228... tailors in the 190s barely break even at 3k, and 188 is a reasonable skill to start working on robes. I don't want to ruin the market for them by indulging the pricewar dude who's been running around lately. And even though, yeah, I make nice money at 3k, I do think it's a fair price for my time. (I also do free combines with materials provided, so it's not like I'm trying to fleece anyone, just charging for the convenience factor.)<br>
<br>
Looking into my crystal ball, I can tell you what's likely to happen if the pricewar continues. I want 242 skill desperately, so I can make my Tunarean armor. I want 250 so I'll be set to go on the new stuff with PoP. Robes are my easiest route to this, because I won't pay inflated bazaar prices for acrylia ingredients (again, I have the cash and the success rates, but I won't teach sellers that it's ok to fleece tailors). I can forsee muling off all my robes rather than take the time to play headgames with whoever's undercutting prices. When I get filled up and/or when I hit 250, there's gonna be one big 'ol sale on robes. Even while trying to be a responsible tradesman and telling customers that this is a one-time deal to get rid of the inventory that got me to 250, I bet folks (especially those kit makers who are our best customers, eh?) will start saying &quot;robes are only worth 1k&quot;... and then where will you be?<br>
<br>
I really had the urge here to say &quot;wanna play games? I guarantee you that you'll lose&quot;. I could buy components and give robes away FREE to get to 250 if I really wanted to. But as much as the little undercutting games irritate me, I really truly don't want to spoil the economy. There are half a dozen tailors with higher skill than me who wouldn't be affected much, but well over a dozen below me who'd also like to make 250 some day. So please, if you've been playing the undercutting game, think about whether eroding prices while gaining no new customers to the market, really is in your best interests.<br>
 <p>-Itienne Sleepstealer, 59 chanter, &ltSans Requiem&gt, Xev<br>
